<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="354" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,1039,1640]" pageId="25" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,373,1039,1064]" pageId="25" pageNumber="354">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
This species can be recognized by its quadrate head, the thickened apex of the clypeus (see Pitts 
<emphasis box="[207,262,1076,1100]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="354">et al.</emphasis>
2010a: Fig. 41), the mid coxa with a median denticle present on the inner margin and diagnostic genitalia with which it shares features only with 
<taxonomicName authority="Pitts" authorityName="Pitts" box="[624,826,1111,1136]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnalduri">
<emphasis box="[624,764,1112,1136]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="354">S. arnalduri</emphasis>
Pitts
</taxonomicName>
(see Pitts 
<emphasis box="[956,1016,1112,1136]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="354">et al.</emphasis>
2010a: Fig. 65), while lacking any mesosternal processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
